Hi Team,

As part of the ongoing RadarLive MQS source reconciliation testing, we’ve been analysing both the forward and reverse reconciliation trends between the Athena CSV source and the MQS flow data.

A couple of observations from the latest analysis that we wanted to highlight for further investigation on the source side.

1. Reverse reconciliation – significant records missing from CSV

After the source-side logic change introduced around 14 April for identifying records to be included in the CSV extract, we are seeing a noticeable increase in records that exist in the MQS flow but are not present in the CSV file itself.

This is especially visible from mid-April onwards, where the reverse reconciliation % dropped significantly compared to earlier periods.

From testing so far, this suggests the updated source extraction logic may be excluding / not capturing a large set of valid MQS records in the CSV generation process.

2. Forward reconciliation

The forward reconciliation % currently appears very high (~99%+), however this is somewhat misleading because the denominator itself is reduced when records are missing from the CSV source.

In other words:

records that never make it into the CSV are naturally not counted in forward reconciliation,
so the forward % alone does not fully represent end-to-end completeness.

That said, there are still a small number of examples where records are present in the CSV but missing in the MQS flow, which also needs investigation from the MQS side.

3. Trend observed

The reverse reconciliation trend became noticeably worse after the April source-side change, particularly from:

mid-April onwards,
with a growing gap between MQS totals vs CSV totals.
